00149   // Mixin class for AST nodes that should behave like vectors. Uses the
00150   // "Template Method" design pattern to allow subclasses to adjust their flags
00151   // when certain objects are pushed.
00153   template <typename T>
00154   class Vectorized {
00155     vector<T> elements_;
00156   protected:
00157     size_t hash_;
00158     void reset_hash() { hash_ = 0; }
00159     virtual void adjust_after_pushing(T element) { }
00160   public:
00161     Vectorized(size_t s = 0) : elements_(vector<T>())
00162     { elements_.reserve(s); }
00163     virtual ~Vectorized() = 0;
00164     size_t length() const   { return elements_.size(); }
00165     bool empty() const      { return elements_.empty(); }
00166     T last()                { return elements_.back(); }
00167     T& operator[](size_t i) { return elements_[i]; }
00168     const T& operator[](size_t i) const { return elements_[i]; }
00169     Vectorized& operator<<(T element)
00170     {
00171       reset_hash();
00172       elements_.push_back(element);
00173       adjust_after_pushing(element);
00174       return *this;
00175     }
00176     Vectorized& operator+=(Vectorized* v)
00177     {
00178       for (size_t i = 0, L = v->length(); i < L; ++i) *this << (*v)[i];
00179       return *this;
00180     }
00181     Vectorized& unshift(T element)
00182     {
00183       elements_.insert(elements_.begin(), element);
00184       return *this;
00185     }
00186     vector<T>& elements() { return elements_; }
00187     const vector<T>& elements() const { return elements_; }
00188     vector<T>& elements(vector<T>& e) { elements_ = e; return elements_; }
00189   };
00190   template <typename T>
00191   inline Vectorized<T>::~Vectorized() { }

00832   // Binary expressions. Represents logical, relational, and arithmetic
00833   // operations. Templatized to avoid large switch statements and repetitive
00834   // subclassing.
00836   class Binary_Expression : public Expression {
00837   public:
00838     enum Type {
00839       AND, OR,                   // logical connectives
00840       EQ, NEQ, GT, GTE, LT, LTE, // arithmetic relations
00841       ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, MOD,   // arithmetic functions
00842       NUM_OPS                    // so we know how big to make the op table
00843     };
00844   private:
00845     ADD_PROPERTY(Type, type);
00846     ADD_PROPERTY(Expression*, left);
00847     ADD_PROPERTY(Expression*, right);
00848     size_t hash_;
00849   public:
00850     Binary_Expression(ParserState pstate,
00851                       Type t, Expression* lhs, Expression* rhs)
00852     : Expression(pstate), type_(t), left_(lhs), right_(rhs), hash_(0)
00853     { }
00854     const string type_name() {
00855       switch (type_) {
00856         case AND: return "and"; break;
00857         case OR: return "or"; break;
00858         case EQ: return "eq"; break;
00859         case NEQ: return "neq"; break;
00860         case GT: return "gt"; break;
00861         case GTE: return "gte"; break;
00862         case LT: return "lt"; break;
00863         case LTE: return "lte"; break;
00864         case ADD: return "add"; break;
00865         case SUB: return "sub"; break;
00866         case MUL: return "mul"; break;
00867         case DIV: return "div"; break;
00868         case MOD: return "mod"; break;
00869         case NUM_OPS: return "num_ops"; break;
00870         default: return "invalid"; break;
00871       }
00872     }
00873     virtual void set_delayed(bool delayed)
00874     {
00875       right()->set_delayed(delayed);
00876       left()->set_delayed(delayed);
00877       is_delayed(delayed);
00878     }
00879     virtual bool operator==(Expression& rhs) const
00880     {
00881       try
00882       {
00883         Binary_Expression& m = dynamic_cast<Binary_Expression&>(rhs);
00884         if (m == 0) return false;
00885         return type() == m.type() &&
00886                left() == m.left() &&
00887                right() == m.right();
00888       }
00889       catch (std::bad_cast&)
00890       {
00891         return false;
00892       }
00893       catch (...) { throw; }
00894     }
00895     virtual size_t hash()
00896     {
00897       if (hash_ > 0) return hash_;
00898       hash_ = left()->hash() ^ right()->hash() ^ std::hash<size_t>()(type_);
00899       return hash_;
00900     }
00901     ATTACH_OPERATIONS();
00902   };

00996   // Argument lists -- in their own class to facilitate context-sensitive
00997   // error checking (e.g., ensuring that all ordinal arguments precede all
00998   // named arguments).
01000   class Arguments : public Expression, public Vectorized<Argument*> {
01001     ADD_PROPERTY(bool, has_named_arguments);
01002     ADD_PROPERTY(bool, has_rest_argument);
01003     ADD_PROPERTY(bool, has_keyword_argument);
01004   protected:
01005     void adjust_after_pushing(Argument* a)
01006     {
01007       if (!a->name().empty()) {
01008         if (has_rest_argument_ || has_keyword_argument_) {
01009           error("named arguments must precede variable-length argument", a->pstate());
01010         }
01011         has_named_arguments_ = true;
01012       }
01013       else if (a->is_rest_argument()) {
01014         if (has_rest_argument_) {
01015           error("functions and mixins may only be called with one variable-length argument", a->pstate());
01016         }
01017         if (has_keyword_argument_) {
01018           error("only keyword arguments may follow variable arguments", a->pstate());
01019         }
01020         has_rest_argument_ = true;
01021       }
01022       else if (a->is_keyword_argument()) {
01023         if (has_keyword_argument_) {
01024           error("functions and mixins may only be called with one keyword argument", a->pstate());
01025         }
01026         has_keyword_argument_ = true;
01027       }
01028       else {
01029         if (has_rest_argument_) {
01030           error("ordinal arguments must precede variable-length arguments", a->pstate());
01031         }
01032         if (has_named_arguments_) {
01033           error("ordinal arguments must precede named arguments", a->pstate());
01034         }
01035       }
01036     }
01037   public:
01038     Arguments(ParserState pstate)
01039     : Expression(pstate),
01040       Vectorized<Argument*>(),
01041       has_named_arguments_(false),
01042       has_rest_argument_(false),
01043       has_keyword_argument_(false)
01044     { }
01045     ATTACH_OPERATIONS();
01046   };

01498     bool exclude(string str)
01499     {
01500       To_String to_string;
01501       bool with = feature() && unquote(feature()->perform(&to_string)).compare("with") == 0;
01502       List* l = static_cast<List*>(value());
01503       string v;
01504 
01505       if (with)
01506       {
01507         if (!l || l->length() == 0) return str.compare("rule") != 0;
01508         for (size_t i = 0, L = l->length(); i < L; ++i)
01509         {
01510           v = unquote((*l)[i]->perform(&to_string));
01511           if (v.compare("all") == 0 || v == str) return false;
01512         }
01513         return true;
01514       }
01515       else
01516       {
01517         if (!l || !l->length()) return str.compare("rule") == 0;
01518         for (size_t i = 0, L = l->length(); i < L; ++i)
01519         {
01520           v = unquote((*l)[i]->perform(&to_string));
01521           if (v.compare("all") == 0 || v == str) return true;
01522         }
01523         return false;
01524       }
01525     }

01840   /* '::' starts a pseudo-element, ':' a pseudo-class */

01847            name == ":after"        ||
01848            name == ":first-line"   ||

01853     ADD_PROPERTY(string, name);

01860     // A pseudo-class always consists of a "colon" (:) followed by the name
01861     // of the pseudo-class and optionally by a value between parentheses.

01863     {
01864       return (name_[0] == ':' && name_[1] != ':')
01865              && ! is_pseudo_class_element(name_);

01868     // A pseudo-element is made of two colons (::) followed by the name.
01869     // The `::` notation is introduced by the current document in order to

01872     // accept the previous one-colon notation for pseudo-elements introduced

01874     // :after). This compatibility is not allowed for the new pseudo-elements
01875     // introduced in this specification.
01876     virtual bool is_pseudo_element()
01877     {
01878       return (name_[0] == ':' && name_[1] == ':')
01879              || is_pseudo_class_element(name_);
01880     }

01882     {
01883       if (is_pseudo_element())
01884         return Constants::Specificity_Type;
01885       return Constants::Specificity_Pseudo;
01886     }
01887     virtual Compound_Selector* unify_with(Compound_Selector*, Context&);
01888     ATTACH_OPERATIONS();

02115   template<typename SelectorType>
02116   bool selectors_equal(const SelectorType& one, const SelectorType& two, bool simpleSelectorOrderDependent) {
02117     // Test for equality among selectors while differentiating between checks that demand the underlying Simple_Selector
02118     // ordering to be the same or not. This works because operator< (which doesn't make a whole lot of sense for selectors, but
02119     // is required for proper stl collection ordering) is implemented using string comparision. This gives stable sorting
02120     // behavior, and can be used to determine if the selectors would have exactly idential output. operator== matches the
02121     // ruby sass implementations for eql, which sometimes perform order independent comparisions (like set comparisons of the
02122     // members of a SimpleSequence (Compound_Selector)).
02123     //
02124     // Due to the reliance on operator== and operater< behavior, this templated method is currently only intended for
02125     // use with Compound_Selector and Complex_Selector objects.
02126     if (simpleSelectorOrderDependent) {
02127       return !(one < two) && !(two < one);
02128     } else {
02129       return one == two;
02130     }
02131   }
